ll be tuned, its tuning fork must walk on two careful feet and carry a green light through places that do not echo.\",\n      \"objectives\": [\n        \"Sound the Fourth-Rib Bone Flute at dawn beneath the Cathedral of the Third Rib and record harmonic deviations.\",\n        \"Use the Resonant Star-Glass Forks to test gate cadence at the First Rib Sluiceworks with Suri Yal’s supervision.\",\n        \"Visit Sternum Plaza at dusk and check the central inlay for frost-script whispers related to flow or oaths.\",\n        \"Report findings to Lysa Truin at the Pale Collegium.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Lysa Truin\", \"lines\": \"The city is an instrument, Iriel, and of late it will not hold tune, no matter how gently we coax the strings of bone and ledger. The reliquary wards sustain a low C of consolation, yet the sluice gates throb in a fretful F that grates the teeth and sets the oath-cords quivering in their frames like frightened harp strings. I have listened from archive galleries and from the back steps of the Collegium kitchens, and the same sourness hides in every echo that returns to me. Go where oaths and water meet, listen with care at dawn and at dusk when truth is least shy, and bring me not just measurements but the shape of the hurt your marrow hears between them. If the ribs begin to creak against each other, the Seven Ribs will not hold us long, and all our clever arguments will become mere breath lost over the River of No Echo. Take the flute, test with the forks, and write on bone or on your own palm if you must, but do not let the city’s song drift without a witness. And if you feel the old taboos tug at your sleeve, remember we honor them best by preventing the need to break them.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Iriel Vask\", \"lines\": \"I’ll follow the hum from altar to gate and mark any seam where it slips, and I will walk slow enough to hear the footfalls between the notes. The flute still answers the ribs if I 