g C and another to the sluice’s fretful F until their beat-note writes its invisible pulse in your bones. With Suri’s scowl for courage, you brace on the crown of Gate Three and breathe through the bone flute so softly that only the gate’s oldest bolts might hear you, shaping the tone to coax the misaligned cadence into meeting you halfway. You whisper counts with the crew, time your tap to the moment the river pauses between insistences, and feel the metal listen with a grudging patience. The gate answers with a tremor that is not fear but memory, and you taste iron and old prayer as if a cathedral had leaned down to drink from the river and left a drop in your mouth. The risk is neither small nor theatrical: a wrong pitch could turn pressure cruel and drag a worker under or crack a bearing for a season, but sometimes a city demands courage expressed as skill and not as speeches. When the tremor settles, the throbbing F softens a half-step, and you know you have stolen a mouthful of disharmony and taught it the beginning of a better word.\", \"outcome\": \"The immediate cadence improves just enough that the crews feel the change as confidence in their hands, and Suri calls you by your first name without the armor of sarcasm for the first time. Your notes record a living response from the gates, a small but vivid proof that the city’s bone and iron will answer gentle correction before they require surgery, and Lysa circles these passages so hard the ink nearly pierces the page. At the Plaza, your frost-script seems to echo the adjustment with a line that curls like a softened gear tooth, and Brother Halin remarks that sometimes the best prayer is a well-timed breath. The Riverwardens file no complaint because nothing broke and because crews who sleep easier make fewer mistakes, though a few older hands spit for luck and ask you not to make a habit of music near their wages. Rival guild whispers insist you played games with taboos, but the Order hears your account an